    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1880-06-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1880-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="647" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d647">
                <head>No. 647.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Farman</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Evarts</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Agency
                                        and Consulate-General of the United States at
                                    Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>,<lb/>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1880-06-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 29, 1880</date>.
                                (Received July 24.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 416.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform, you that I
                            sent you on the 12th instant, from Alexandria, the following telegram:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p rend="flushleft">Secretary <hi rend="smallcaps">Evarts</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington:</hi>
                        </p>
                        <p>Commander Gorringe sailed two o’clock to-day with obelisk. Will
                                    call at Gibraltar.</p>
                        <p rend="right">FARMAN.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>A telegraphic dispatch received on the 23d instant from the commander
                            from Gibaraltar informed me of his arrival at that place, and that
                            everything was working admirably well. The steamer was in good condition
                            on her departure, and I have no doubt will have arrived in New York
                            before the receipt of this dispatch.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>E. E. FARMAN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
